 society, and what are the countervailing social forces (including those deriving from law, politics, and religion) with which it has to contend? Theodore Brown seeks to answer such questions in this magisterial work of synthesis about the role of science in society. In Part I, he elucidates the concept of authority and its relation to autonomy, and then traces the historical growth of scientific authority and its place in contemporary American society. In Part II, he analyzes how scientific authority plays out in relation to other social domains, such as law, religion, government, and the public sphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aSciencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aBrown.  aautonomy.  aepistemic.  aethics.  agovernment.  aimperfect.  alaw.  amoral authority.  aoracle.  apolitics.  apower.  apublic sphere.  areligion.  ascience.  asociety.  atechnology.  aunited states.  aus.  ausa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271050935?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271050935423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271050935/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK